latestIgtvVideos.caption:
I haven’t had much luck with graduations in the past. During my middle school graduation, I fainted before making it on stage and was rushed to the hospital. And in high school, I had food poisoning. 

Today was the first of two graduations ceremonies and I got to walk alongside my fellow graduates of the @parsonsschoolofdesign BFA Fashion Design Program. Thank you @marie_genevieve_cyr @jane.k.francis and everyone who nominated me for the opportunity to speak to the Class of 2022. Proud to say that this graduation was the best one yet. 

One chapter of my life has come to an end, but another is just beginning. I’m so excited for what’s to come!

4 years of studying fashion design at the @parsonsschoolofdesign have led me here today. After 5 years of working in fashion with over 10+ internships, both paid and unpaid, I came to realize that my passion was no longer in design and that I was looking for something more impact-driven in the field through inspiring and motivating others.

Even though our industry has come a long way in the past couple of years, part of the overall fashion industry’s strict barrier to entry relies heavily on the presence of unpaid internships. The practice of unpaid internships in fashion and the overall internship structure, in general, conveys the idea that if we pay our dues now and “stick it out” during the early years of our careers, we’ll be granted entry into the exclusive world of fashion and with the job of our dreams. But after years of exposing the industry of these practices, we find that this “rite of passage” into the fashion world comes at the expense of exploitative, manipulative, and unjust treatment.

As a culmination of a year and a half’s worth of research, ideation, and development, I’m very excited to share with you all the resources I am coming out with soon, as a part of my BFA thesis project, to help support students and early career professionals, like you and I, to navigate through unpaid internships and career obstacles that are ever-present in the fashion industry. More to come very soon! 

*Clips were compiled from assorted online documentaries, videos, and news outlets. A big thank you to @faidratzedakis and @giadaggraziano for participating in the interviews I conducted in this video*

latestIgtvVideos.title: Lab to Fashion
latestIgtvVideos.caption:
This semester, as a junior in Parsons, I struggled a lot in trying to identify myself as a designer. There was so much pressure to come up with the most life-changing and innovative ideas that I was pushed and pulled in so many directions. Ultimately through being challenged in my core classes by my professors who never stopped making me delve deeper and deeper, I stumbled upon an idea that meant a lot to me. 

As most of you know, I attended a specialized STEM education all throughout high school and some part of me coming to Parsons, never wanted to lose touch with that side of me, but with this project, I didn’t have to. It was the perfect blend between science and fashion and I can’t wait to look back at this and see how much it grows in the future. 

Over the past month, I’ve been working hard to put together this short documentary/film for my final project. My goal was to introduce my fashion system to the world and to inspire awareness for other people interested in the relationship between fashion and other disciplines. Thank you all for your support in this endeavor:

latestPosts.caption:
Looking at my social media, it’s hard to understand my journey of how I got here and all of the rejection I inevitably faced throughout the process. Rejection, especially in my industry, is so normal and I don’t talk about it often, but I had to face it—and still do—all throughout my career. Just wanted to share that you are not alone in your experiences and just because the successful people that you follow don’t talk about it, just know we all had to go through it. Hope this helps and let me know if you want to see more like this ❤️

Inspired by my twin sister’s post @alyxandriaang
